For continuously compounded interest, we have the formula &lt;math> \displaystyle A = Pe^{rt}&lt;/math> where ''A'' is the amount, ''P'' is the principal, ''r'' is the rate, and ''t'' is the time.

We are given that &lt;math> \displaystyle  P=10000, A=100000, t=2&lt;/math>. Plugging these in yields

:&lt;math>
\begin{align}
100000 &amp;= 10000e^{2r} \\
10 &amp;= e^{2r} \\
\ln 10 &amp;= 2r \\
r &amp;= {\color{blue} \frac{\ln 10}{2}}
\end{align}
&lt;/math>
